            <p>The objectives of this course are to provide a basic methodology for studying at the university.  The course, as a university-wide, intends to encourage students to consider 'how to live' and 'how to study'.</p>
            
            <p>Specifically, the course consists of three parts: 'university theory,' which deals with what a university is; 'learning theory,' which deals with how to learn at a university; and 'career theory,' which deals with how to design one's future.  To put it simply, the course starts with a discussion on a way to study at the university and develops broadly into the consideration of future plans.</p>
            
            <p>The classes are conducted in both lecture and workshop formats.  Question and answer sessions about guest speakers' lectures and group discussions (for example, on essential differences between learning at high school and at the university) are incorporated.  In last year's final class, students were asked to write about things they need to do right now as a pledge of their determination and to post them on the blackboard. (<a href="index.php?lang=en&mode=c&id=36&page_type=top">See photograph.</a>)</p>
            
            <p>The class atmosphere is relaxed and exchanges of opinions are initiated by introducing the workshop style to provide students with opportunities for mutual discussions and to have them present the details of the discussions.</p>
            
            <p>The evaluation (assessment) of performance of students participating in this course emphasizes students' daily learning activities.  The course provides assignments to be accomplished for every unit, in addition to commentaries on specific topics that the students are instructed to write in every class.  The students' achievements are rated in terms of overall points.</p>
            
            <p>Through my experience of conducting this course, I have realized, as a professor, that many students want to enhance their learning activities at the university but cannot find effective advice about doing so.  It can be said that the courses offered at the university should provide younger students advice on finding a place where they can be themselves, having meaningful relationships with their friends and faculty members, and learning based on their own initiative.</p>
            
